animal.description:
Lucky came to us when he was hanging out in the middle of a busy road; just laying there. The lady did not want to see him get run over, or injured, so she loaded him up and a Deputy met her here to impound him. No one has claimed him. 
He has had quite the life and the battle scars to prove it. He has seen his share of fights- his face is scarred, and his back foot has found a snare or something similar to it in the past. He has a healed scarred back foot that does not bother him 
He is true to his breed, he is not good with other dogs. We tried a foster with him because their dog was so sweet and gentle. We have added his foster mom's comments below. 
He will need a truly escape proof fence as he has been allowed free rein in his past life and he looks for ways to escape.
Here at Paws, he is absolutely no trouble. He is house trained, sleeps on his nice comfy bed, doesn't bark and is genuinely a sweet guy. 

Lucky was very calm and gentle while he was here, but he was quick when he wanted to escape. He seems to get too hot indoors, but is house trained and did let us know when he wanted out and did not chew on anything in the house. 
If a door is even cracked a little he will push through, and he does not come back when his name is called or other common recall commands, but he definitely does know his name and would *sometimes* come when called if we called him in an excited tone. He seems to actively search for an escape route and did appear to be afraid he was in trouble for running off, because he would whine and roll over as soon as I got out of the car to bring him back. He's such a sweet, gentle giant who loves head pats. He loves duck treats, but didn't show interest in any of the toys I got for him. He just loves exploring. He was good with my dog because she left him alone when he made it clear he wanted space. 
You were right, he just has some special needs, the main one being a yard he can't escape at all, or he will take off down the road. He is just a sweetheart! Thank you for all you do for these sweet animals!!

If you feel you can help this guy, we would love for you to come and meet him!

animal.description:
I am 45 lbs., 4 years old, and l am looking for my forever home.

Adoption Donation: $450

All dogs are microchipped, neutered, current on all vaccines, heartworm tested and started on Tri Heart Plus; Vectra 3D.

All household members and any dogs from the household need to be present at the time of the adoption.

Our website is always kept 100% up to date with who is currently available.  As soon as animals are adopted, they are moved to the Adopted Pets page so if they are still listed on the Adoptable Dogs or Cats page, they are still available. So keep any eye on the site for any animals being added as available for adoption as new animals are added everyday! We would recommend if you haven’t done so already that you submit a general online adoption application with us so it is on file for when you are ready to come out and adopt. The adoption counselors will be able to show you many that would be a good fit for your family. Animal House Shelter can not guarantee breed or breed mix of our adoptable animals. The animals are posted on the website as a breed or breed mix based on their physical characteristics they most resemble. We also can not guarantee the ages of our adoptable animals or how large puppies will be when fully grown.

Please fill out an online adoption application. Visit our 'Adopt' page to view adoption process steps, policies, requirements and FAQ. View our 'Visit' page for hours and directions to our shelter. We look forward to seeing you soon!

animal.description:
Hi, my name is Charlei, and I know the spelling of my name is wrong, but that is what it is. I tell everyone its Old English, for Charlie.

I need a new home. You see my mom did something really bad. She has kids! All was great before, so now I am acting up as there are now TWO of them invading my peaceful home. I am a very lucky fellow as I had some great years, now it's gone.

I need a get out of jail card now!!! As you can see I am real cute and a great guy at 6 years old. I need a new home as an only dog. A single guy or gal would be grand as I like to protect my owners from interlopers. I am a big guy of unknown Westie mix gene pool and I weigh in at approx 40 lbs. Yep, That right, I am extra large so there is more to love.

Sunshine State Westie Rescue - Florida folks have told me that they will find a new home for me, which turned out to be the luckiest thing of all this mess. They promised to take really good care of me and pick out only the right home. I am with my original owners as my home gets lined up. So HURRY up and pick me!

The Westie Rescue-Florida lady wants to tell you some more stuff, but I can't wait to meet you and come live with you forever. XOXO, Charlei

Please take a few minutes and go to the website http://westierescue.com/. Take a look at the Frequently Asked Questions to familiarize yourself with all the factors affecting your decision to adopt a rescued westie like Charlei. If you think you could be the perfect forever home for a rescued Florida westie, please fill out and submit the Adoption Application. PLEASE MAKE CERTAIN TO FILL OUT EVERYTHING COMPLETELY. The incomplete applications are filed until someone has time to get back to them, which unfortunately, in an all volunteer organization, could take quite a while. When your finished, send an email to: aggie.sswr@gmail.com to let her know you are interested in my big butt. She will smile and say "Congrats".

animal.description:
Samson was born in October of 2016 and came into rescue because he nipped two people when they came into his wireless fenced yard area.  This is not uncommon for this breed, as they protect everything within their area. He was also in a wireless fenced area, which is one of the many reasons why wireless fencing does not work for this breed.  He is a friendly and outgoing boy, who enjoys human attention, and who does well with other dogs.  He was previously with chickens in the past, and does not harm them.  He is unproven with cats.  He is a fence jumper, and will need a 5' - 6' fenced area.  He was a house dog the past few years, and also spent time outside too.  If you have free range chickens, and a structure for shelter, not a lean to or dog house, and a 5-6' fence, Samson could be the boy for you.   To apply for him, send a message to info@igpr.org to receive a livestock guardian application. 

 We recommend obedience training for all newly adopted pyrs, to help you create a special bond with you and your new friend, and so you have a well behaved canine. Great Pyrenees are willing to learn, but are not as eager to comply with commands as much as other breeds. They are bred to be independent thinkers. Applicants must be over 25, own their own home and all children in household must be over 6 years old. Your resident pets must be up to date on vaccines, sterilized, you must have a good history of vet care for them, and you must have used heartworm preventative year round for your dogs. 


Samson can be placed as a livestock guardian, but he will need a structure, not a lean to, or dog house for shelter.  You must have  5'-6' fenced area. 
 He can also be placed as an inside pet with outside privileges. You MUST have a securely fenced 5'- 6' fenced yard accessible from your home. Invisible fencing does not work with this breed and they will take the shock for the freedom, or bite anyone who enters their territory.  Great Pyrenees are bred to roam and will create their own territory if not secured, which can led to them being lost, hit by vehicles or shot by people who see them as a threat. The breed is not a good off leash dog, and cannot be trusted to not run away.  A Great Pyrenees off leash is a " DisAPyr." 

If you are interested in adopting or fostering, please complete the appropriate application on our website, www.igpr.org under the Adopt tab. 

All of our dogs marked as needing foster homes are also available for adoption.  If a dog is listed on this site, it is available.  No need to contact us to see if it is,  We do require you  complete the adoption application prior to meeting a dog.

We also offer a foster to adopt program. You foster the dog, and have first right of refusal on them if an approved application is submitted for them. 

In fostering a dog, the dog comes to you fully vetted. and groomed. You provide good quality food, grooming, and we provide the heartworm preventative and medical care, if needed* .(*Based on approval from IGPR.)

Adoption fee is $300

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.ADOPTION PENDING!! I am so very thrilled for my sweet little lady Amy that she met her parents last night. It was a 100% love-fest all the way around. She was nervous at first, sure it's so confusing for all these dogs seeing all these new people wearing masks, but after they took their time, sat on the floor with her, fed her small pieces of meatballs -- she was able to be sure they only wanted to love her.
Her Mom & Dad are even going to get a new fence installed for her safety & enjoyment so it will be a while before that can happen but she is 'Going Home' to be the beloved baby girl & start her new life. She's even going to be living nearby here in DE so I'll get to see her & babysit as needed. She will be my #565th adoption since 2-24-2004! Amy's 'Meet Your Match' designation is Teacher's Pet - I've got the whole package - smart, four legs, love to learn, and live to please. Go ahead, teach me anything. Sit, stay, balance your checkbook, I can do it all. Keep me entertained, and I'll be yours forever. **Be sure to look at Amy's videos & photos below**
I'm Amy's foster mom & she is a pure delight! She's very smart, so much so that you can see her thinking & most of all she wants to please. She also seems to love -- love -- love kids which here at LNF makes her a 'Bona-Fide Kid Lover!' She was introduced to several little girls from 8-10 years old & she just wiggled all over with joy & rolled over to give everyone 'belly' at meeting them! She actually does lots of wiggling -- she is a true wiggle-butt!
NO KITTIES! I feed birds & squirrels, so I have many of them out front on my lawn. When she comes back from a leash-training session, she really wants to chase them!
She's truly such a good young lady, and very sweet & friendly & generally comes when I call for her. I would say about 90% of the time. She has had extensive professional training & as stated before, she really wants to please you & tries to figure out what you want from her.
She's just turned 1-year old & she still has lots of puppy in her behavior. She's petite at only 35 lbs. I don't have children, so I have not been able to test her but given her gentle disposition, I'm sure she'll love kids as much as people -- but she will need to be tested with kids to be sure.
You can see how shiny her coat & very short & very soft! She's housebroken & she goes to the backdoor to let you know to let her out to potty. Amy does not want to potty in the house!
Here is a photo of her on my sofa with her girlfriend Reese. She has earned the right to be in my home & on my sofa. She loves other dogs, but given her youth, she can get rough & sometimes she has to be corrected -- which she accepts.
She would love to be adopted into a home with another dog, but it should be with another young playful dog like her -- so they can be buddies. An older, more mature dog would not enjoy her always wanting to play.
What she adores, most of all, are sticks - I put a photo of her in when she is happiest - when she has found "a stick!" When she's out on a training walk or in my fenced-in yard, she's always on a mission to find them. She's such a fun-loving, playful baby girl! The other thing she LOVES is water! When I bring the hose out to clean & fill up the water bowls she loves to play in the water. (There is a video of her showing her joy) & she loves ice as much as water. She stomps on ice & throws chunks up in the air with complete abandon!
If she sounds like the kind of young girl you would like to bring into your life & home, be sure to read our adoption requirements first & if you can meet or exceed them, you can apply online. Both are listed on the left side of our website.
We accept or credit cards & PayPal for the adoption fee.
~ All LnF pups/dogs have been temperament tested & live in a foster home. ~ All pups and dogs have been housebroken (puppies are paper trained) & crate-trained and have had basic training ~ All pups/dogs have been Microchipped ~ Tested for Heartworm, Ehrlichia & Lyme ~ Each dog is on Heartworm Medication & Flea/Tick year-round while in our care ~ Up to date with Rabies ~ Distemper, Parvo & Leptospirosis vaccines ~ de-wormed.
Our adoption fee includes (30) days of FREE pet insurance with an option to purchase -- but there is no obligation. We strive to provide the BEST medical care available so that YOU are assured all our pups/dogs are healthy, up-to-date on all necessary shots, spayed, or neutered by our rescue.

Click here to watch a video of Amy/ADOPTION PENDING!!. 1/26/21 9:55 AM

1/21/21  I've been neutered and my teeth and gums are just fine now.  I'm ready.....come and get me!

I'm a sweet pup, but I was never neutered so my family turned me into the county shelter because I "humped" a lot.  Being approx. 10 years old I should have been neutered unless I was used for breeding.  I'm a good looking fellow so that's a possibility.  Anyway I'm getting neutered.  My teeth are awful.  My first vet check found 2 teeth just hanging with a thread.  The vet removed them and I feel much better.  I'm o.k. with other pups and I'm sure I'd be fine with cats, but not sure.  I'm a gentle little soul.  My foster moms biggest complaint is I'm not potty trained completely.  I go outside, but sometimes I hike my leg.  Not good, but I know I can get better.  I could have been an outside pup.  I do love being inside, so I say I'm an inside pup.  I'll soon be ready for my forever home.

animal.description:
This gorgeous fluff ball is our very sweet Pickles! A few months shy of her birthday, Pickles' biggest wish is to be able to celebrate it with her own furever family. Pickles is believed to be a purebred Pyr, she only came to us because her previous owners had their own health issues to tackle with and were unable to adequately care for Pickles. These days, Pickles has settled in wonderfully in her foster home, and is an exceptional playmate with her foster siblings. Pickles has this superb ability to win you over in a few seconds with her puppy charm - she is adorably sweet, and absolutely LOVES being hugged or brushed. She is happily playful, just as a young dog her age should be, and will happily show you her invented games so you can be involved as well :) Pickles still has a lot to learn, but she is a fast learner and always eager to please, making training sessions a fun and rewarding experience for her and her people. Pickles would love to have a family who has the time to help with her training and guide her along as she adjusts to new environments; in time, Pickles will no doubt mature into the pyrfect companion who will bring you years of joy. Now, who wants to grant Pickles her wish in time for her birthday?

NYS Registered Rescue # RR102
View full listing, fee and online application at - www.nationalpyr.org/adoptable-dogs (sorry, no phone submissions, but if you would like more information you can email us at renpyrgroup@yahoo.com).

Secure VISIBLE fencing is required; invisible fencing WILL NOT contain this breed. 

Our goal is to assess every application on its own merits. Key considerations are: 1) the experience of the applicant with large breed dogs 2) children in the household or regularly visiting the household are ready for a large-breed dog who is a guardian by nature (www.nationalpyr.org/know-the-breed) and 3) the sex of other dogs currently residing in the household to avoid same-sex aggression issues. For puppies under six months old, the applicant’s ability to socialize the puppy with older dogs is a priority.

If you are interested in adopting me please go to www.fureverunitedrescue.com to fill out an application. 

I am in a foster home in South Texas, and will be transported to the Pacific Northwest once adopted. 

People friendly but is reactive to other dogs without proper introduction, he is sweet but nervous so he barks. Needs a strong handler who will work with him. Great boy. Good with kids.

TOTAL FEES FOR ADOPTION:   Adoption Fee of $275 + Texas Sales tax of 8.25%  + $150 transport fee for a total due of $447.69. The adoption fee includes all age appropriate vaccinations (spay/neuter, microchip, health certificate) and the transport fee covers transport to the Pacific Northwest on the next available date).

TRANSPORT: Currently we have monthly transports. It will be up to the adoptive family to meet the transport to pick up your new family member. Please be advised that our dogs are adopted to their forever families prior to being transported to the Pacific Northwest. Unfortunately at this time, we cannot bring dogs for a typical meet and greet situation, due to the extensiveness of the transport distance and it being unfair for the dogs who are not adopted to have to make the trip back. 

Due to the number of requests that we receive on our puppies and dogs, please be advised that all adoption applications are processed in the order received. Once we send you an application, your place in line does not get reserved until your application is returned to us.

animal.description:
Meet Frisco!

*Frisco is in our Houston foster program and will be able to travel in February.*

Hey new friends, my name is Frisco. I'm 8 years old and 75 pounds. I was living on the streets in Houston for a while until I came to live with my foster mom. When I got here I had bad eye and ear infections, and although I didn't fully trust her, I let my foster mom treat my infections and was never sassy to her. She says I don't have a mean bone in my body. Since my infections got all cleared up, it's been determined that I don't see or hear to well anymore, so it takes me a bit to warm up. I'm housetrained, but when I get to your home I ask that you please don't give me full access to the house right away, at least until I know my surroundings a bit. This will help me to learn where I need to go to get outside to go potty. I get along with other gods of all sizes, who are calm and can show me the ropes of my new home. I'd actually really love another dog around, but if you don't have one that's okay, I have confidence that you, as my new family, will help me learn my way around my new environment! I'm a bit curious about cats, but I'm not mean to them, and I don't chase them. I would do okay with older kids too. I just need them to understand my seeing and hearing issues, so no little ones please. 

Since I was living on the streets, I'm having a good time learning how to be a dog in a home environment, and playing is one of the things I'm learning. I have a sister dog here that plays with the humans, and I try to watch her and follow her lead. Since I don't see too well, I will sometimes take your hand in my mouth, but I never do this to bite or hurt you, I'm just not sure how to play yet, so please don't be scared, but instead help me learn. I walk really close to my people so I know where to go, and this makes me feel more comfortable. Sometimes I will mouth your shoes while we walk, but with time and training, I'm certain I won't do this for long. I really like going places with my humans once I know I can trust them, but the act of riding in the car isn't my favorite activity. I sure hope I find a family soon, who is willing to help me be a dog and work with me to build a bond that is unbreakable! Maybe that's you?

Albert's Dog Lounge is a transporting dog rescue, meaning that we rescue many of our dogs from high kill shelters in areas of dog overpopulation. We are a specialty rescue focusing primarily on senior and special needs dogs.  The vast majority of our dogs come from the Houston, TX area where we have an entire team of volunteers, coordinators, and fosters. We do also work with local shelters, rescues, and owners.  If you apply for a dog that is currently in our local Houston program, we will work to get your dog transported to WI as quickly as possible. We ask that you have patience during this time of uncertainty and unprecedented dog adoptions nationwide. 

Learn more about Albert's Dog Lounge, our mission, and adoption policies by visiting Albertsdoglounge.org. 

Our process includes an approved application, reference checks, a homevisit, and then a meet and greet with the dog. Adoption fee is $275.

Begin your application process by copying this link into your web browser: https://www.albertsdoglounge.org/apply

animal.description:
Georgia is a 2 yo female Husky/Terrier mix weighing approx. 40 lbs rescued from a North Carolina Shelter.

Georgia is a gorgeous husky mix who is looking for a furever home. She had a rough start to life and ended up in a high kill shelter in North Carolina. Due to her rough past, she needs patience and someone who is willing to teach her the world and things aren't scary. She is so smart and currently has already mastered "Sit" "Stay" "Kennel" "Timeout" and "Get out". She loves playing with her dog foster brother Roscoe and they do everything together. She does need slow introductions to other dogs and would do best in a home with a submissive dog her size or larger. She will require a 6 foot fence or an owner who will never leave her outside unattended due to her husky instincts to look for things to keep her busy lol. She would be an amazing candidate for training and LOVES to impress you. She has learned so much and has come so far in her short time at her foster home, she would truly make an excellent addition to anyone's family. She is kennel and potty trained and LOVES her kennel.

** NO Cats or small animals for Georgia

If you would like to meet Georgia please complete an online application that can be found at: http://hopeanimalrescueofiowa.org/forms/196/dog-application

Adoption fee is $250 which includes spay/neuter, age-appropriate vaccines/tests, and microchip.

animal.description:
Terrin is a one year old Heeler mix ready for his forever home.  He is a lover of all people and would love a home  that will keep him as part of the family (walk/play) and also allow him to snuggle up with you in the evening. He would be best with a family with older children and breed experience.

If you are interested in learning more about Terrin, please complete an application and then reach out to roxy@bigfluffydogs.com

If you are interested in adopting this dog, please apply online, at https://bigfluffydogs.com/adopt/adoption-application/. 

Our main website, www.bigfluffydogs.com has more information about us and the rescue process. 

NOTE TO EMAILERS FROM PETFINDER: WE DO NOT RESPOND TO EMAIL INQUIRIES WITHOUT AN APPLICATION. WE REGRET WE CANNOT RESPOND TO EVERY EMAIL, BUT UNLESS YOU FILL OUT AN APPLICATION, WE DO NOT KNOW YOU EXIST. 

All known information about an individual dog is provided in its listing. We do our best to provide accurate information, but adopters should understand that each home is different and the dog may behave differently in a new home. Dogs are creatures of their environment and you help make the dog what it will be. Homes considering adopting a puppy must be prepared for 1.) Flexible schedules for potty training. Puppies can only hold it for one hour per month of age (i.e. a 4-month-old puppy can only go 4 hours without a potty break). 2.) Crate training until the puppy is at least one year old to prevent chewing on inappropriate things when you can't supervise. 3.) Socialization.  The more positive and varying experiences as a puppy the better, both in and out of your home. 4.) Puppy behavior and life stages are equivalent to a human toddler. It takes at least a full year to have a calmer, well-adjusted dog. Patience is required and when your dog's behavior is a positive experience for you and those around you, your patience will be rewarded ten-fold, for years to come.  Please do not consider adopting a puppy if you have not thoroughly thought through the pros and cons of having one. So many people end up returning them after 3-5 months because they didn't realize the amount of work involved in raising a puppy.  Patience, appropriate toys, socialization, and obedience training are all musts. All are time-consuming and can be expensive. All dogs require supervision with children and obedience training. Adopters that want to have good dogs must be prepared to put the time and effort into training a dog. Any dog requires work and effort, but a well trained, well-socialized dog is more than worth the effort to get them there.

animal.description:
Hi my name is Inka. I’m 4 years old and 47 lbs. I came all the way from Puerto Rico to find my furever family. So far, here’s what the volunteers at ODHS have to say about me:  

When Inka arrived he had a lot of pent up energy and quite frankly, he needed to be neutered!  Since that has happened, wow, he has really mellowed out. He’s now so sweet, curious (but not obnoxious), and much more gentle. He walks pretty well on his leash (and that gets better everyday too). He plays nicely with other dogs. He crates well too. He’s a handsome fellow with a great personality.  He will be a wonderful dog for his furever family. Below, is information from his Puerto Rico foster: 

Inka is a very intelligent boy. He likes to be the alpha male and has alot of pent up energy that he needs to get out. Inka is very sweet but also very sensitive. He doesn't like to be yelled at and he doesn't like to be handled roughly ( like for medical things or "helped" into a crate). He has been through alot and needs an understanding family.

You can still come adopt me or even join our foster program to help the humans learn all the awesome things about new dogs like me! Learn more on our website! 

Hope to see you soon! 

What breed am I? Mixed mutt! ODHS does not breed label (unless there’s official paperwork), as studies show it is nearly impossible to tell the exact breed of each dog based off of their appearance.

Educational article:
3/3/3 rule:
https://www.rescuedogs101.com/bringing-new-dog-home-3-3-3-rule/?fbclid=IwAR2iv5m7fqk3FieO7LOsstGeGsYYV_F1rJOd1BPxaImofLpcinpYsUbFRWs

Please remember to bring a collar and leash (non-retractable) with you the day of the adoption. Note: Martingale collars and slip leads are strongly recommended.

Due to COVID19, we aren't having as many open, public adoption events.  Current schedule is pre-determined meet and greet appointments are Wednesday evenings and on Saturday from 12-2.  
 Our adoption center is located at 3602 Lafayette Blvd, Suite 102, Fredericksburg, VA 22408. It's important that you keep an eye on your emails for any changes or updates during the adoption process.

Visit our website for an application to adopt. 
https://www.olddominionhumanesociety.org/adoption-application

Old Dominion Humane Society is a volunteer based organization. We are run completely by volunteers, who also have full time jobs, so we appreciate your patience.  Currently, the average timeframe for a response to your application is 1 week.

and be a part of promoting forever homes for dogs in need.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Interested in adopting? See our adoption proccess.
KOA
Who's a good boy? Koa's a good boy...suuuuuuuch a good boy!! This pup will do best in a home of his own where he can get a lot of activity and attention. He loves people and especially getting belly and ear rubs. He walks great on leash and does very well in the car, so will be a joy to hike with! He knows 'sit', 'down', and is very receptive to voice, even coming when called. This polite boy will also give you his paw for a shake! With all that intelligence there has to be a little malamute mischief and here it is...he can open doors! So typical of his breed, he will need a secure space and activity so he doesn't get bored and decide to take himself for a walk. That challenge is easily overcome by ensuring he is exercised and engaged - which will be super easy with his personality - I mean who wouldn't want to pay him all the attention? As one of our volunteers aptly put it, Koa is 'ready to hop up on his forever couch soon'!Interested in sponsoring? See our sponsorship information.

Calliope is a one year old (41 lb) Kelpie / Australian Cattle Dog mix. She loves toys, treats and going for walks. Calliope will do best with a family who has experience and patience with an active dog. She does well riding in the car.

Calliope does best with larger dogs or would be fine as an only dog. She is recovering from FHO surgery and her new family will need to continue her PT exercises at home for a couple more weeks, so she can continue building back the muscle in her leg.

Calliope has a fair amount of energy and will need daily exercise as well as mental stimulation. She is no couch potato! Once her needs are fulfilled, she likes to relax and hangout with her people. She is about 90% potty trained, but continued structure will get her to the 100% mark.

animal.description:
Tall, dark & handsome young man seeks adoptive family that loves outdoor activity and adventures – running, urban mushing, hiking, camping and more with at least one other large-breed, playful canine companion. I love playing with other dogs and they help give me confidence to explore the world. 
 
Children confuse me and give me anxiety. No children; teenagers would probably be ok. I am very weary and very scared to meet new people or be in loud & busy places. My adoptive family will need to have experience with fearful dogs and a lot of patience.
 
I do have house manners but I absolutely need consistency, boundaries and continuous training. I go urban mushing 3-4 times a week, in addition to daily walks, multiple but short training sessions throughout the day and love playing with puzzle feeders every day.
 
Application Requirements:
6 foot fence or higher. 10 foot fences with lean-ins are not required but advantageous.
Previous German Shepherd, Belgian Malinois or Siberian Husky ownership & training experience is required.
Geographic exclusions apply, e.g. applications may be rejected simply based on home location. Home location must be within 5 hours driving distance from the greater Los Angeles area. 
At least one other large-breed, active canine companion is required.
No children; households with teenagers may be considered.
Interview & home visit are required.
 
Jack will be 1 year old in February. He is a German Shepherd/Malamute mix with a sprinkling of Siberian husky, Samoyed and other breeds. He is currently 80 pounds and will likely be 100+ pounds when fully developed. He is neutered, microchipped and current on vaccines.

animal.description:
****Please do not message the rescue asking if this dog is still available; if a dog/puppy is still listed on Petfinder, we are still accepting applications for them. PLEASE READ ENTIRE BIO BEFORE EMAILING****

*Name: Faith 
*Age: 10-11 years 
*Current Weight: 99lbs 

*Rescued from: 
*Adoption fee: $250
*Health: up to date on required vaccines requires daily meds and supplements  for arthritis 

Faith is a super sweet old lady that loves to relax on a comfy bed, or lay out enjoying the sun! She is house trained, never chews and stays out in the house alone. She likes other dogs but she has a hard time getting around sometimes due to her arthritis, and would do best with a calm dog. She likes to go for short walks, and does great in the car (just needs a little help getting in!) She is a 99 lbs Rottweiler mix, and is about 10-11 years old (maybe older). She has osteoarthritis and takes Gabapentin and Rimadyl to help her get up and down, and around easier. When she is feeling good, she is a very happy girl and loves human attention! She is truly a sweet heart, and deserves to live out her golden years in a relaxing, loving home! 
Faith  was rescued when she was near death in a rural shelter in Texas; an area where there is an abundance of homeless dogs, and not a lot of shelter space for them to go while they wait for their forever homes. Faith had contracted a bad case of pneumonia and she was fighting her life when we rescued her! She pulled through like a champ and deserves a second chance. To apply to adopt Fairh fill out an application at www.snarrnortheast.org/applications. 
**Meet and greets will not be scheduled without an approved application.**

IMPORTANT: This dog has not yet been altered. For any dog or puppy that is not able to be spayed/neutered prior to adoption, SNARR requires a $125 deposit in addition to your adoption fee, as well as a strictly-enforced signed Spay/Neuter Contract stating you will have this dog altered within 6 months of adoption. The $125 deposit will be returned once the contract has been fulfilled. 

-------------------------------------------------------
FAQs -- PLEASE READ ALL BEFORE EMAILING
-------------------------------------------------------
**Please note that SNARR NE is a volunteer-based organization. While our volunteers will try to respond to you as quickly as possible, it is helpful if you review the following information about our adoption process before emailing:**

- LISTED BREED(S) & AGE: We are taking our best guess on age, breed, and size when fully grown, based on the puppy's/dog's physical appearance and what we might have learned about one or both parents depending on the situation. *NOTE* We rarely know a dog's exact age, nor are we able to tell the true or full breed mix of dogs as our information is limited most of the time. Because we often do not have access to medical records at the time that we are posting dogs to Petfinder, there are sometimes discrepancies between what is posted on Petfinder and what might be listed on a dog's medical records.

- SNARR'S ADOPTION PROCESS: The first step in adopting or meeting a SNARR dog/puppy is to fill out an application at www.snarrnortheast.org/applications. Once we receive your application, one of our adoption application processors will contact you, review our adoption process with you, and answer any additional questions you may have. **We do not go on a first-come-first-serve basis for adoptions, but on best fit for a family and most importantly the puppy or dog.**

- MEETING ADOPTABLE DOGS: Meet and greets will not be scheduled until after your adoption application has been fully processed by one of our adoption processors.

- APPLYING ONLINE: If you fill out an online application, please do so from a computer (not a mobile device), make sure you answer ALL the questions in as much detail as possible, and that you receive a confirmation email. If you do not receive a confirmation email, that means we did NOT receive your application.

- PUPPIES: We do suggest listing a 1st, 2nd and 3rd choice on your application if applying for a puppy with several litter mates.

- ADOPTION FEES:  $495 for puppies / $375 for adults. Adoption Fees for Seniors, Special Needs and Bonded Pairs vary

Hi my name is Lucas! I’m 1 year old and weigh 38 lbs! I am a happy ball of fun!!! LETS PLAYYY!!!!! I love other dogs, and toys, and bones, and teddy bears! I am great at entertaining myself to I will play all day if I could. I would love a fun family to take me to see all kinds of new things in life! I also ride great in the car so we can go wherever you want. 

I just arrived to ODHS but the humans promised to update my bio as they learn more about me! I traveled all the way from Puerto Rico to find my furever family! I'm what you call a street dog, the product of little to no spay/neuter in my area. 

You can still come adopt me or even join our foster program to help the humans learn all the awesome things about new dogs like me! Learn more on our website! 

Hope to see you soon!

animal.description:
Harley is a young adult male (2.5 years) weighing 68 pounds.  There is something very special about Harley, which you will realize for yourself when you meet him.  Although he has had a difficult life up until recently (he used to live with a homeless person who had to give him up), you would never know it from his personality.

There is one word that best describes Harley: Sweet sweet sweet. Harley is the sweetest dog his foster mom has ever cared for (and that is saying something!). He is a big baby that loves to be on your lap and just chill on the couch. Harley’s tail never stops wagging! He can also be very active; he loves to play fetch. 

Harley is well behaved.  He walks well on a leash. He can sit, stay, give paw, lay down and come. He has no food aggression with his own food and does not bother people when they are eating.

If you would like to adopt Harley (and we sure hope you do!), please reach out to Safe Paws Rescue and they will send you an application to begin the adoption process. Safe Paws is a small rescue, so they accept inquiries from residents in Pinellas County only, please.

*Name: Titan and Jasper 
*Age: 1 year and 3 years 
*Current Weight: 125lbs and 65lbs 
*Rescued from: South Carolina 
*Adoption fee: $750  (plus $125 spay/neuter deposit each, which is refundable when spay/neuter agreement is fulfilled)
*Health: Both are up to date on required vaccines, microchipped, neutered. Jasper is heartworm+ (SNARR covering treatment)

Titan is a pure bred Great Dane and Jasper is a Shepherd Lab mix. This adorable pair are best buddies and need to be adopted together :-) They were found running loose and when animal control was made aware of who their owner was and checked their living conditions, they seized the dogs. Jasper and Titan lived in a tiny outdoor pen which was very dirty and unkept. Despite where they came from, these boys are super friendly and social and very good boys! They both tested well with other dogs too. Titan is Heartworm negative and will need to be adopted with a neuter contract. Jasper is HW positive and the rescue will provide his medication for whoever adopts him. These boys deserve a great home where they can stay together and be spoiled and loved!  

Titan and Jasper are currently waiting for their forever home at SNARR's Adoption Center in Brewster, NY. They arrived in NY on 1/16 and quickly became a favorite pair among SNARR’s volunteers! To apply to adopt or foster this awesome duo, please fill out an application at www.snarrnortheast.org/applications. 
**Meet and greets will not be scheduled without an approved application.**

-------------------------------------------------------
FAQs -- PLEASE READ ALL BEFORE EMAILING
-------------------------------------------------------
**Please note that SNARR NE is a volunteer-based organization. While our volunteers will try to respond to you as quickly as possible, it is helpful if you review the following information about our adoption process before emailing:**

- LISTED BREED(S) & AGE: We are taking our best guess on age, breed, and size when fully grown, based on the puppy's/dog's physical appearance and what we might have learned about one or both parents depending on the situation. *NOTE* We rarely know a dog's exact age, nor are we able to tell the true or full breed mix of dogs as our information is limited most of the time. Because we often do not have access to medical records at the time that we are posting dogs to Petfinder, there are sometimes discrepancies between what is posted on Petfinder and what might be listed on a dog's medical records.

- SNARR'S ADOPTION PROCESS: The first step in adopting or meeting a SNARR dog/puppy is to fill out an application at www.snarrnortheast.org/applications. Once we receive your application, one of our adoption application processors will contact you, review our adoption process with you, and answer any additional questions you may have. **We do not go on a first-come-first-serve basis for adoptions, but on best fit for a family and most importantly the puppy or dog.**

- MEETING ADOPTABLE DOGS: Meet and greets will not be scheduled until after your adoption application has been fully processed by one of our adoption processors.

- APPLYING ONLINE: If you fill out an online application, please do so from a computer (not a mobile device), make sure you answer ALL the questions in as much detail as possible, and that you receive a confirmation email. If you do not receive a confirmation email, that means we did NOT receive your application.

- PUPPIES: We do suggest listing a 1st, 2nd and 3rd choice on your application if applying for a puppy with several litter mates.

- ADOPTION FEES:  $495 for puppies / $375 for adults. Adoption Fees for Seniors, Special Needs and Bonded Pairs vary

animal.description:
Meet Gertie! Gertie is a shy, petite, pittie lady, 50lbs, around 3yrs old, fully vetted and HW Negative. She loves people but is a bit weary of anything new. Her Favorite thing is to cuddle, she is very gentle and would make a great companion. She tolerates other animals (dogs and cats) and likes to play outdoors, indoors she wants nothing more than a couch and you. She walks very well on a leash and enjoys any time she gets to spend with you. She does well in a crate, she still has her meals there, but has progressed to sleeping on a dog bed in the bedroom. She is potty trained, unless it's cold outside then she will use a puppy pad. She hates cold and humid weather, and refuses to be exposed to it. She is soft spoken, she very rarely barks. However, she will occasionally grunt or sigh. Gertie has done well around children, but will do best is a calm environment as she's still gaining confidence and is easily startled. She is very sweet and appreciative. I think Gertie will adapt to almost anything as long as she is properly introduced and given time. She has obviously had a rough go in life and deserves to have warmth and love for the rest of her life. Can you open your home and share your couch with this sweetie?

To set up a meet and greet or inquire about a dog, please first fill out an application at https://savinghoperescue.org/contact. It doesn't obligate you, but it is the first step. We don't get to all of the inquiries but respond to all applications. Thank you for choosing to rescue!

animal.description:
Hi there. My name is Boone. I was brought here by some very nice people that found me wondering about. I had an ulcerated paw, which really hurt and my choke chain collar was way to tight and had started to imbed in my neck. The people here give we medications and I am all healed up. My fur will take a while to grow back on my neck were it was shaved. My tail was never bobbed so I do have a long tail. I know Rotties normally have a bobbed tail so I am special cause I do not! I am approx. 1 year to 2 years but very puppy like. I am a big love bug. I would like to be on your lap! OK at approx. 99lbs that is a lot of lap dog I know but still. Snuggles then. I love to play ball. Run the yard and have a blast!!! Who knew life could be this fun! I am a strong boy and I am a hand full on leash but working on that. I know how to sit and give paw. So I am a smart boy and good learner. As for other dogs I would say maybe a girl friend would be OK but NO male dogs! I have to check out the cats too. I can let you know later how that goes. As for little people. I think if they are nice and have manners with a dog I could like little people especially if they will play ball with me! So I am hoping to find a active fun loving family. We will all have a great life together and have lots of fun!

Boone met Ned the cat. He had to be encouraged to check him out. He barked at him once which startled us all but that was it. For the most part he had no interest. Ned seemed comfortable. I would suggest a highly monitored case as running loose is not the same as crated! Cat runs he could decide to chase.

animal.description:
COURTESY LISTING--- INFORMATION AND CONTACT IS LISTED BELOW. 

My name is Val and I'm an approximately 5 year old pit bull, lab mix. I had a rough start to life being neglected and abused by humans only to be dumped at the shelter. I had suffered a broken ankle and hip which had been left untreated and had skin infections and was underweight. I laid shaking in the back of my kennel too scared of what would happen to me next when a dedicated volunteer took special notice of me and got a team of dog lovers and rescue organizations to get me out. 

I was lucky enough to find my way to a trainer who helped me learn how to trust again, build my confidence, and teach me how to be a good house dog. My trainer fell in love with me and decided to keep me but sadly medical issues force her to find another loving home for me. Maybe you're who I'm looking for!

What You'll Love About Me: I am such a sweet (and sensitive) young man. I absolutely love snuggling and giving kisses. I will do anything for a tasty treat and I will chase a ball but have no idea that I should bring it back to you! I am absolutely adorable launching into the pool to make splashes that I chase and can keep myself entertained doing this for quite some time. 

I am potty trained, rarely bark, know how to rest quietly in my crate, never guard food or toys from people, and am not stressed if my humans are gone. I'm very polite while driving in the car and I love a good nap and also chewing on a nice bone.

What I Need in a Home: Because of my past, I can be a little shy (especially with strange men) so I'm looking for a home without big parties or lots of visiting strangers....I'm not aggressive, just a little unsure. I don't have a lot of experience around young kids so it's probably best I don't live with them either.

I'm more of a home body and am not the kind of dog who would enjoy going to busy spaces. So a house with a quiet neighborhood to walk in or just a nice yard for me to get my wiggles out in is perfect.

I can also be dog selective (I like some dogs once I've gotten the chance to know them) but my trainer thinks it's best I am the only dog in my home just to make sure I'll feel safe. I have previously met cats and did fine with them and I can be retested around kitties if needed. 

Adopting Me: If I sound like a good fit for your home and you're dedicated to helping continue my journey in trusting humans and believing the world is a safe and wonderful place, please get in touch with Erin at Tug Dogs by emailing: tugdogacres@gmail.com or call/text 916-426-6469. I am currently living in the Sacramento area. A home inspection will be required to adopt me (may be done virtually due to Covid) and transition/training support will be provided.

animal.description:
Hi friends. I'm Lily, aka Mama Lily, aka Lily Pad . Like many of those before me, I'm from Texas, with a heart just as big. Love hard and snuggle harder, that's my motto. My life BB (Before BUR) was a sketchy one, one I'm trying to forget. I also had heartworm and missed a transport while I recovered, but was able to come up last Oct. My life AB has been pretty good. I'm still learning to trust, I love everyone I meet when I'm given the chance, and I even have a new puppy friend. We take walks together, AND I have booties for when it's snowy. Don't really know about kiddos and other critters, since my foster mama doesn't have any of those. 
 Living inside is a new experience. Really made a place for myself in the big, comfy chair. I get to sleep there all night too. I don't really like being home alone but foster mama always comes home so I'm getting used to it. I just love to snuggle, and take walks, they're my favorite things in this new life. That's all I'm really looking for...
 Well, my doggy doctor says I'm ready to go, so if you think you would like to add me to your family, please send in your application. See you soon!! Apply on our website: www.buffalounderdogs.com

 

*our adoption radius is with 45 minutes of zip code 14226, US only.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Mama Martina is a stunning 7 lb brindle chihuahua who they estimated at approximately 1-2 years old. She came into rescue with two beautiful babies. The babies are ready to find their new homes and Martina is too!!

Martina is the epitome of a chihuahua! She is a Velcro dog and is literally glued to your lap. She had no sense of personal space and loves her people with all she has. She is friendly to strangers but she does bark at anyone entering the home initially. She has been around an 8 year old child and has done fine. As well as cats. She lives with other dogs and tolerated them but her true love is of her people.

Martina does know what to do when taken outside but in true small dog fashion she will also sneak and pee on occasion especially when it's cold or rainy. She does have pee pads available to her in her foster home. She has been on a leash a few times but will need more work on this in her forever home.

She does sleep in a puppy pen with her puppies but she does not like being in it. She also hates the crate. She has a high pitched shriek she lets out when she is done and is relentless until you let her out. She will probably do better gated in a room or left loose while you are gone.

Martina has made herself right at home with her foster family and would love a family all her own. She is a lap dog and will want to be allowed on your furniture. She will make a wonderful companion for someone and we can't wait for her to find the perfect family for her!

Martina is spayed, up to date with vaccines, microchipped, flea/worm treated and tested neg. for heartworm. Her adoption fee is $400

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.If interested in any of our animals for adoption, or to foster an animal, please fill out the respective application here to get the process started. Visit our FAQ webpage for commonly asked questions about our adoption/foster process.
My name is Petey and my owner of 7 years recently passed away. Now I wait for my new forever people. No one is entirely sure how I feel about dogs yet. I am not sure how to react to them on walks and could use a little help learning to walk better. I am a strong boy with a bit of a prey drive. But in the house I am very sweet and have never thought about touching anything that's not mine, including food on the counter. I love stretching, belly rubs, making funny snorting noises, and playing. I would love a fenced yard to run around with a tennis ball. I can get very excited and make some scary noises but soon you'll learn that I just want to play. (I can be a bit exuberant, and at 70 pounds, maybe would inadvertently knock a little person over, but never on purpose.) As long as I've had my daily exercise, I am a big couch potato and will sleep all day. I could even be a good running companion with a little training. Please fill out an application - I would love to meet you! Click here to watch a video of Petey Pooh.Last Day Dog Rescue now microchips all animals before adoption. Microchips are implanted between the animals shoulder blades and are a permanent form of identification. The microchips are registered to Last Day Dog Rescue with the adopter's info added once adopted. If the animal is ever lost and slips his/her collar/tags the microchip allows the finder to know who to contact if scanned for a microchip. Animals MUST still have a collar with tags on at all times. Per our contract, we take all our animals back if for any reason you can't keep your adopted animal.

Please understand the statements about this animal are based upon the foster home's evaluation of the animal. The animal might behave differently (negatively or positively) in your home. While the animal might be good with the current foster's dogs, cats, children, etc., it may not be with your animal(s) or children. The animal may be housebroken or litter trained in the home of the foster but may relapse in your home. The animal is represented to the public as it performs in the foster home and any statements made regarding the animal are conditional to that foster home setting. Please understand that statements made regarding this animal are simply overviews and are not guaranteed.

The Petfinder.com system requires that we choose a predominant breed or breed mix for our animals. Visual breed identification in animals is unreliable so for most of the animals we are only guessing at predominant breed or breed mix. We get to know each animal as an individual and will do our best to describe each of our animals based on personality, not by breed label.

Thank you for looking through our list of animals needing forever homes and choosing rescue first. We appreciate you stopping by.

animal.description: Domino is a 53 lb, 2 year old male terrier mix who is a fun-loving, high energy, extremely smart dog, totally housebroken. He loves to run, dig, jump and chew big sticks. He will return toys and balls that you throw but doesn't like to let go, he likes to shake it with you. Speaking of shaking, he will shake hands, sit and beg, if you say ''belly rub'' he will roll on his back to get a good rub. If you ask him what he wants, he will go to the jar where the dog cookies are and hit it with his nose. Or, he will bump your leg if he wants to go out. He loves to sit in the chair with me and he sleeps in our bed very well. He is very attached to his owner, fearful of other people and animals. He would do well with a fenced yard and being the only dog. His adoption fee is $200.00~~If you are interested in this animal, you can complete a questionnaire at http://www.hbpr.org/hb-adopt-web.html, email homeward@ellijay.com, contact us on facebook at https://www.facebook.com/HBPR30540/ or call 706-698-4663.Thank you for considering a rescue dog or cat! Don't shop when you can adopt!

animal.breeds_label: Black Mouth Cur & Australian Shepherd Mix
animal.description:
Gravity is a gorgeous sterling color and always likes to be the caboose in the feeding lineup! His momma Venus was pulled from an Oklahoma shelter just in time to give birth in her foster home on 1/10/21. Gravity wants a furever home that can provide a safe and loving environment for a new puppy to learn and explore. He will be available for adoption when he turns 8 weeks old on March 7th. More info and pics to come as he grows!

Since this puppy may be too young to be altered at the time of adoption, the adopters will be provided with a voucher to have the puppy altered and microchipped by the time he is 6 months of age. This must be done at Nebraska Humane Society. If you prefer to take the puppy to your own vet, we will pay a PORTION of the cost ($69) to your vet of choice.

The suggested adoption donation for Gravity is $500. We are a 501c3 organization which means that your donation may be TAX DEDUCTIBLE. Your donation goes toward the high cost of veterinary care for our animals in rescue, as well as providing supportive services to animals in homes.

Information about the adoption process: All adoptions require a completed ADOPTION APPLICATION. Once your application is approved, we will put you in touch with the dogs foster to see if you and the pet are a good match. If so, we will arrange a meeting for you and the pet. The adoptions for all of our animals will take place in the Omaha, NE area and must be done by the adoptive family in person. We do not ship or deliver.

Please Note: We are a RESCUE, which is different from a shelter. We conduct veterinary and personal reference checks during the application approval process. We always select the right applicant for each dog, based on the dogs needs. If you and the dog are not a good match, we will help you select another dog, or we will keep your approved application on file for 6 months.

To learn about Muddy Paws Second Chance Rescue or donate to our animals, please visit our website at MuddyPawsSecondChanceRescue.com or our Facebook Page.

animal.description:
Eclipse has a gorgeous onyx coat with sable legs. He is the second biggest of the litter. His momma Venus was pulled from an Oklahoma shelter just in time to give birth in her foster home on 1/10/21. Eclipse wants a furever home that can provide a safe and loving environment for a new puppy to learn and explore. He will be available for adoption when he turns 8 weeks old on March 7th. More info and pics to come as he grows!

The suggested adoption donation for Eclipse is $500. We are a 501c3 organization which means that your donation may be TAX DEDUCTIBLE. Your donation goes toward the high cost of veterinary care for our animals in rescue, as well as providing supportive services to animals in homes.

Information about the adoption process: All adoptions require a completed ADOPTION APPLICATION. Once your application is approved, we will put you in touch with the dogs foster to see if you and the pet are a good match. If so, we will arrange a meeting for you and the pet. The adoptions for all of our animals will take place in the Omaha, NE area and must be done by the adoptive family in person. We do not ship or deliver.

Please Note: We are a RESCUE, which is different from a shelter. We conduct veterinary and personal reference checks during the application approval process. We always select the right applicant for each dog, based on the dogs needs. If you and the dog are not a good match, we will help you select another dog, or we will keep your approved application on file for 6 months.

To learn about Muddy Paws Second Chance Rescue or donate to our animals, please visit our website at MuddyPawsSecondChanceRescue.com or our Facebook Page.

animal.description:
This is sweet Eva!

Beautiful Eva is a 4-year-old American Staffordshire Terrier. She is spayed, current on her vaccinations, microchipped, and ready for her happy ever after.

This poor girl was rescued after being dumped in horrible conditions. She was emaciated, flea & tick infested, had masses on her body, and some of her teeth had been filed or removed. Yet, through the horrible life she has endured, she is full of love and kindness. She's gentle, she loves everyone she meets including children. She is even perfect in the home and is housebroken. Eva is best as the only dog.

She has the sweetest disposition and only wants to love and to be loved. Are you ready to give Eva her happily ever after? If so,

please submit a completed
adoption application found
at www.doggiebonez.com so that we can schedule a meet and greet. He is also on all of our social media pages IG: @Doggie_Bonez_Inc_ and Facebook: Doggie Bonez.

If adoption isn't an option, please consider fostering one of our pups. We are a volunteer-run non-profit dog rescue and always welcome new short or long-term doggie foster families. We much appreciate the help and time of our fosters. You provide all the love, comfort, and safety of a home, and we supply you with everything else you may need, dog food, dog bed, toys, medical attention (if required), etc. If you are interested, please visit www.doggiebonez.com to see all of our available dogs who need a foster family while waiting for their fur-ever home and complete the foster application.

animal.description: Ford is an inquisitive, playful, loving little guy. His interests include treat puzzles, naps, zoomies, and sunbathing. Ford's most distinguishing features include big, perky ears and a smile that takes up his whole face. Ford came to APA! after he was believed to have been hit by a car. His back legs are still a little clumsy, but he doesn't let that stop him from having a good time! If stumbles, he gets right back up and keeps going. He's still a little unsure about the stairs, but he's gaining more confidence climbing up every day! Ford is the perfect co-worker. His foster mom works from home and he lays quietly on his bed beside her either playing with a toy or taking an afternoon snooze. He does snore, but don't worry, it's cute! He's also really good at pawing at her to let her know he needs to be let outside to potty. Ford is great on a leash and loves exploring all the sights and smells of the neighborhood. He doesn't pay much mind to other dogs out for walks, but he always wags his tail and smiles at people walking by! Ford would love a home with another dog to call his friend. He has a blast chasing his foster sisters around the yard and playing tug-o-war. When he starts running faster he leaps and catches some air - it's so cute! His favorite pastime in the yard is running up the hill, rolling down and then running back up to do it all again. Of course, he'll only do it a few times before needed a puppy nap. He loves spending time outside playing and sunbathing, so a house with a yard would be ideal. Will you be Ford's fur-ever home? Be sure to follow him on Instagram for adorable photos @Adopt_Ford_APA! or @ford.is.on.automatic.

animal.description: Beautiful, big boy Atlas is just over 1yrs old and currently weighs 98lbs.  We expect him to exceed 100lbs when fully grown.  He is a very friendly, social boy that will be a wonderful family dog.  He loves long walks, hiking trips and playing in the yard so an active family is required.  He is a typical shepherd so can be somewhat protective of his family when other dogs visit in the home so he must be the only dog.  When outdoors and away from his home, he does love to play with other large dogs.  He has great house manners and has some basic obedience but additional training will help him continue to be a well balanced pup.  Because he is such a large boy, kids must be over 14yrs old and he MUST have a large breed, German Shepherd experienced home.  He must also have a 6ft securely fenced yard... the bigger the better!

animal.description:
Meet Frigo - a handsome pup currently hanging out in his Connecticut foster home till he finds his forever family. 

Frigo is just about 3 months old (d.o.b. 10/19) and was born with a wonky eye. He has partial vision out of that eye and gets around perfectly fine (it should not get worse, but will not get better). 

He is a total love bug. He currently lives with a cat and another dog, and gets along well with everyone - he would love a home with another playmate to keep him entertained. 

All of our animals are examined by a veterinarian, given age-appropriate vaccinations, de-wormed, microchipped, spayed or neutered, heart-worm tested, and treated if necessary. Vet references and a home/family visit are required, and an adoption fee applies. 

Visit www.pmarinc.org for more information, and to fill out an application.

*Please note that due to COVID we are taking extra precautions. Pre-adoption visits are at the discretion of the foster home, and transport options are not available. In most cases, prospective adopters will need to pick up the pup at the foster home.

animal.description:
Haku has the kind of eyes you could stare into for days! Haku is a 5 year old, white Great Pyrenees who has experienced some ups and downs in his life and his owner knew he deserved more so made the hard choice to surrender him to rescue. Haku was originally saved from an owner that was mistreating him but his current owner feel onto some hard times which lead to a move where Haku had to be kept outside. Understandably all of these changes have made him a little anxious, confused and depressed. Thankfully a foster home has stepped up to take this sweet boy in and we're happy that we can now provide him with the needed medical care (he has a growth on one of his hind legs), grooming, and decompression time he needs. Haku is leash trained, knows sit and down, sometimes enjoys car rides. He is a big baby who loves cuddles and playing with rubber toys, he is a couch potato.

To see the most up to date adoption status of this dog, please visit www.bigdogshugepaws.com
This is just one of hundreds of gentle giants available for adoption at BDHPI! It is best not to get your heart set on any one particular dog upfront because there is no guarantee they will still be available once you are approved or that they are even the right match for your family. Purebred puppies are only eligible for adoption to giant breed experienced homes.

animal.description:
Hi friends! I’m Basil! I’m a 9 month old, female Collie/Terrier Mix. I’m about 40 lbs and a LOT of energy. I have a puppy diploma in basic skills and manners class, I am potty trained, and I am looking for a family that is experienced with training that wants to continue to teach me skills. I am very smart and eager to learn, my foster parents work with me every day.
 
Things you should know about me:
1.     I love dinner time! I will hop around on my hind legs from PURE JOY at the sound of food.
2.     I am working on my manners around crates, gates, and doors… sometimes tough (treats help), I love to jump and whine and bark sometimes.
3.     I have THE FLUFFIEST tail. It curls over my back and it's really cute, probably my most adorable feature, other than my cool fur pattern.
4.     I LOVE playing with my foster dog siblings, but sometimes I struggle with meeting new dogs when I am on a leash. I’m getting better with this in training.
5. I am awesome at playing fetch!
 
I haven’t been tested around cats or kids, I think I would very much like to chase them, like I try to chase squirrels while on walks. My prey drive is strong. Also, I am very good at catching stink bugs :)
 
I know you will get lost in my loving stare, and make me yours!
 
Love,
Basil

animal.description:
** PLEASE READ DESCRIPTION FULLY BEFORE APPLYING THROUGH OUR WEBSITE BIGLOVEANIMALRESCUE.ORG **

Meet Godiva! She is a 10-week-old Pitbull mix and weighs about 12lbs! We were originally on a rescue for another dog when our director Lisa spotted Godiva and her brother being transported loosely in the bed of a truck. When Lisa inquired with the drivers, they said the puppies were for sale and Lisa paid them off to bring these babies into our care for medical, and to find them an incredible forever home.

Godiva is super friendly, smart, curious and adventurous. She greets every human and dog with a wagging tail and just as much as she loves to play with her brother and other dogs, she loves for the humans to join. While playful, she is also very laid back and will put herself to bed when she’s tired. According to her fosters, she is nearly potty trained and we’re very happy about that!

Godiva is going to grow up to be a big, strong girl (60-70lbs) and will need a dedicated family preferably with bully breed experience who will give her LOTS of needed daily exercise. Like any of our Pitties, her adopters will be required to invest in training! Applicants must have a backyard and preferably another doggy sibling.

**We are looking for applicants who are based in Southern California and if there are children in the home, children must be 10 years or older.

**The adoption fee is $500. Our rescue covers microchip, vaccinations to her adoption date, and spaying at one of our veterinarians when she's old enough.

**If you're interested in Godiva, you must visit our website and fill out an application here: https://bigloveanimalrescue.org/adoption-application-form/

**No meet and greets prior to approved application.

**Due to the volume of messages we receive on all of our platforms, we do NOT send follow up emails to our applicants and do not reply to messages here on PetFinder. We’re a small, volunteer ran rescue so we can only do so much in 24 hours. Thank you for understanding!

Again, please no repeat emails. If we feel you're the right fit, we will contact you.

www.bigloveanimalrescue.org

animal.description:
Hello everyone! My name is Nora, and I'm a 4-and-a-half year old pittie. I was an owner surrender here at Stray Haven, and I have made myself right at home. I can be a little stand offish when I first meet strangers, but I warm up fairly quickly. I love to run the play yard here, but I also love to nap and to chew on my bone. I like getting attention on my terms, as I can be quite independent. I LOVE treats. They are the way to my heart. Right now, I'm a chunky hippo and could lose a few pounds so don't over do it! I'm such a sweet girl once I get to know you. I'm looking for my fur-ever home and I'm ready to settle down. Sometimes I show some signs of separation anxiety when I'm away from the caretakers. It could be because living in the kennels can be so stressful sometimes, but I tend to bark when no one is around. I can get worked up sometimes around other dogs, so it would probably be best if I were the only dog in the home. I could probably go home with some older kids too. I might be a little rough with youngins. Come stop by Stray Haven so we can meet!! I'd love to eat some treats you wanna give me.
Stray Haven Humane Society & SPCA
194 Shepard Rd., Waverly, NY 14892
(607) 565-2859, www.strayhavenspca.org

animal.description:
Breed: Labrador Retriever mix
Sex: Male
DOB: ~12/31/2014
Weight: 41 lbs
Energy Level: Medium
Personality Type: Sweet, 
History: Surrender/Transfer from animal control
Good With: Dogs
Ideal Home: Low traffic home where someone is home with him much of the time! Apartments could be ok.
Fence Requirements: Not required.
Special Info: Buddy LOVES to go for walks and car rides! He can be a bit protective of his kennel. Buddy can climb chain link fences.

The information we are providing for this animal was developed based on observations and assessments in a shelter or foster environment. We do our best to provide information that will help determine if the dog might be a good fit for you. Please note that behaviors may change in a home environment. We also ask our applicants to assume that any animal they adopt from us will need to be potty trained and learn house manners, although this is not always the case. Our online animal bios are designed to provide as much information as possible and answer some anticipated questions. We do not have the resources to respond to emails with more specific questions.

We are receiving an unusually high number of applications per pet at this time! Please follow the rules below to ensure your application is reviewed; pay attention closely to these instructions because applications will NOT be processed if they are not followed. Please keep in mind that dog/cat availability is currently changing by the hour; you will receive an email if the animal you are interested in is no longer available. New dogs become available almost every day, so feel free to let us know if someone else interests you if your initial choice is already adopted! 

Fill out the application (DOG: https://www.iheartdogs.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/IHD-DOG-Application-9-10-18.pdf, CAT: https://www.iheartdogs.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/IHD-CAT-Application.pdf) completely. Every question must be answered, and it must be signed. If you are going to type your responses, open the application, save it, type your answers, and save it again. 

-Applicants must be 21+ years old and live within a 50-mile radius of our shelter at 22415 Groesbeck Hwy, Warren 48089.

-You must identify at least 1 dog/cat that you are interested in. If there are multiple dogs/cats, number them in order of priority. 

-Scan a copy of proof of home ownership (i.e. tax bill, deed, or mortgage payment - you can black out the account #, etc.) or animal clause/agreement of your rental agreement.

-Attach the application and home ownership proof/rental agreement animal clause to a new email and send it to bark@iheartdogs.org. The subject line must be formatted to read ""#1 choice of dog/cat, Your First and Last Name"". Example: Subject: Fido, Jane Doe
Once your application is received, it will be assigned to an Adoption Counselor who will follow-up with the applicant who is the best fit within a few days, or to discuss other dogs/cats. It could take up to a couple of weeks for you to receive a final disposition on your application so there is no need to check on the status.

-Introductions will be scheduled by appointment only, 45 minutes per appointment. The entire household, including current dogs, must be present for the appointment. The introductions will take place outside in our parking lot.

-We will continue to perform vet checks for current and prior pets in the household.

-Home visits will be in person for the yard and virtual for inside the home.

-Finalizing the adoption will also be scheduled by appointment.

While this process may seem cumbersome, it is interim during COVID-19, and it is designed to help us respond to the volume of emails we receive every day. Since we are receiving a high volume of applications, please be patient if a dog/cat is no longer available. 

Thank you for your understanding.

animal.description:
Hi, my name is Mark and although I am not super outgoing ...Im a good boy!! Im working really hard on my confidence. My foster mom is available 24/7 to tell you all about how perfect and special I am.

 

Once I feel a bit comfortable, I am a pretty funny little dude, similar to a Mexican Jumping Bean; spunky for sure! I have so many toys here I just dont even know how I will find time to play with them all. I really like toys, so if you have toys I can definitely help you play with them. I have had some pretty bad and scary stuff happen to me in the past and I dont want to talk about it. That's why I want to move forward with a patient, forever family and leave that icky stuff behind. 

 

Im not a fan of sudden moments, so screaming children running around the house doesn't sound like a good match for me. It just makes me uneasy. I have a foster sister who is sooooo cool. She is older than me, but she still plays with me and we have a hoot! So if you have another dog, I would really like that and if they happen to be confident that would probably be pretty cool too.

animal.description:
**PLEASE READ ALL - TWO MONTHS AGO I WAS COMPLETELY FERRAL**

 

Hey there everyone. Im Blossom and Im a work in progress. I havent had much human interaction before coming to Fetch and I have no idea what it is to be a house dog, but man Im learning. 

 

Im nervous of people and need time to come out of my shell, but Im learning ear scratchies, treats and cuddles on the couch are pretty nice things. I still get nervous with fast movements (so little kiddos scare me) and retreat to the safety of my kennel when I get nervous so please have patience with me. 

 

Im learning so many new things including walking on a leash (man that stuff touching my neck is annoying! Sometimes I bite at it to try to get it off yet, but just go slow and remind me its no big deal). Im also learning how to potty outside and am doing great! But keep in mind, Im a work in progress and so are ALL my new skills. 

 

I LOVE other dogs and will need at least one fur sibling (but I would love more too). Having other dogs around really helps me loosen up, try new things, and find my confidence. 

 

Im young and I have my whole life ahead of me. I still do puppy things like grab paper towels and shred them (man theyre just so fun) and annoy my foster siblings to play constantly. I hope one day Im not scared when people move off the couch or when I hear a new noise outside, but right now thats where Im at. Like Ive mentioned, work in progress. Im a huge flight risk outside so even if you have a fence, I will always need to be leashed when going outside for potty breaks or play time. 

 

I would love someone with lots of patience and time to help me find my confidence and just be like any other dog. This process could be super bonding for us and I would love you forever for helping me, but it will be a process. Please, if youre interested in me, be willing to meet me where Im at and take extra precautions to keep me safe in your home. 

 

I would really love a family of my own if youre ready for me.

animal.description:
*no apartments*
 

Bishop is a great size dog. His mix is a bit of a mystery. Bishop is roughly 7 years old and from our best guess is a Beagle, Terrier mix weighing about 35 lbs. Pictures of him are deceiving because he looks much bigger but he is a pretty petite dog. He is microchipped, fixed and fully house trained.

Bishop ideally needs a home where hes:

 The only dog, or with smaller dogs, preferably. He loved our Pomeranian but was sometimes scared of groups of larger dogs or in-your-face dogs. He has done well with larger dogs in our home (never on leash) but was never a fan of dog parks. 

 A home without cats. Cats, squirrels and rabbits are practically all the same in his eye and will be chased.

 A home without small children. Hes perfectly accepting of older children, adults, groups and every stranger [ not a great security dog ] He finds children very scary and did bite the toddler in his home after being chased- ultimately leading to his rehoming. 

 Able to be active but also lounge around to his hearts content. He gets spurts of energy but is a very chill, old soul.

 Accepted as either big spoon or little spoon because hes a professional cuddler. 

 A home with a great cook because he hates the sound of the fire alarm and one where pillows are abundant because he takes comfort pretty seriously.

Bishop loves a good nap on furniture but he also knows no. He is allowed on some of our furniture and not others and fully abides, he hates his kennel but can be trusted when away from home (never chews, scratches, barks or counter hops). 

You can also look at our old Instagram account @sabestagrams for more insight into this quirky, loving dog who is sure to win over someones heart as he did ours. Bishop just wants to love and be loved back

animal.description:
Fantine, like many of us, started 2021 a little flustered from a tough 2020 -- but a few days into the new year at her new foster home she has a new lease on life and is excited for what 2021 has in store! At 4ish months and 15 lb, Fantine is the biggest of her litter of 4 but was also nervous at first despite her size. Gentle, curious, and playful she was nonetheless mostly interested in resting in her crate. But after just a day and night in her new foster home, Fantine has totally come out of her shell (and the crate).

 

She loves to play with her many toys, is playfully chatty, super cuddly (so so so soft!), endlessly curious, and always sporting a big grin. She sleeps through the night in her crate other than to tell you she needs to use the bathroom. Out on her walks, she does great on the leash, does her business, likes to say hi to the neighbors and their dogs, and catching her reflection on glass doors. Fantine will make a fantastic dog for just about anyone -- she loves to cuddle and hang out just as much as romping around and adventure -- and she's got plenty of energy for both!

 

Fantine is spayed, up-to-date on vaccinations, microchipped, and heartworm negative.

 

Adoption fee includes the following:


	Spay/Neuter
	Rabies Vaccination
	Distemper / Parvo Vaccines (includes series of 3 for puppies)
	Bordetella
	Microchip with prepaid lifetime registration
	Deworming
